<paragraph id="8BD88A4A5337FFAEFF52FCBFFE9BFCF9" blockId="2.[212,1172,836,1314]" box="[212,320,836,859]" pageId="2" pageNumber="875">
<heading id="D0903D265337FFAEFF52FCBFFE9BFCF9" box="[212,320,836,859]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="2" pageNumber="875" reason="5">
<emphasis id="B91356585337FFAEFF52FCBFFE9BFCF9" box="[212,320,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="875">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD88A4A5337FFAEFF52FC90FD73FA80" blockId="2.[212,1172,836,1314]" pageId="2" pageNumber="875">
Representatives of the genus can be distinguished from the remaining 
<taxonomicName id="4C67F1C95337FFAEFC6BFC90FB4FFC21" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1870" box="[1005,1172,875,899]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="875" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Theraphosinae">Theraphosinae</taxonomicName>
by the presence of reddish or whitish setae (colour of live specimens) on dorsum abdomen, presence of 
<typeStatus id="54DC34E85337FFAEFE52FC57FDD6FC66" box="[468,525,940,964]" pageId="2" pageNumber="875">Type</typeStatus>
III urticating hair, labium wider than long with reduced labial cuspules (from 
<quantity id="4C9F27AF5337FFAEFE51FC30FD9DFC41" box="[471,582,971,995]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" metricValueMax="1.778" metricValueMin="1.27" pageId="2" pageNumber="875" unit="in" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5 to 7 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="4C67F1C95337FFAEFDD5FC37FD11FC41" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1903" box="[595,714,971,995]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Hapalotremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="875" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipes">
<emphasis id="B91356585337FFAEFDD5FC37FD11FC41" box="[595,714,971,995]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="875">H. albipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C67F1C95337FFAEFC88FC37FCA3FC41" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1916" box="[782,888,972,995]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Hapalotremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="875" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis id="B91356585337FFAEFC88FC37FCA3FC41" box="[782,888,972,995]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="875">H. major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), with the exception of 
<taxonomicName id="4C67F1C95337FFAEFF52FC10FE21FBA1" authority="Cavallo &amp; Ferretti, 2014" authorityName="Cavallo &amp; Ferretti" authorityYear="2014" box="[212,506,1003,1027]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Hapalotremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="875" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martinorum" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B91356585337FFAEFF52FC10FE21FBA1" box="[212,506,1003,1027]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="875">Hapalotremus martinorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A220EB235337FFAEFD84FC10FD87FBA0" box="[514,604,1003,1026]" pageId="2" pageNumber="875" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
with 28 labial cuspules in females. It is characterized by the tarsi fully scopulated and divided by rows of setae increasing in width from legs I to IV, with tarsus IV divided by five or six rows of setae. Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C67F1C95337FFAEFF52FBB0FEABFBC1" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1903" box="[212,368,1099,1123]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Hapalotremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="875" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91356585337FFAEFF52FBB0FEABFBC1" box="[212,368,1099,1123]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="875">Hapalotremus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also recognized by the following features: tibial apophysis present with two branches, the prolateral bearing a long stiff black thorn on inner side, slightly curved at tip and of similar size to the spur, the retrolateral with a long spine inserted on inner side at the middle of the spur, metatarsus of leg I noticeably curved at base, and male palpal bulb with embolus subcylindrical curved to the retrolateral side with conspicuous subapical keel. Females may be also recognized by the single spermathceal receptaculum.
</paragraph>
